recently returned from R=C3=A9flexion Charlevoix in the rugged, mountainous=
 terrain of northeastern Quebec, where I was celebrating my 65th birthday.<=
br/><br/>Before getting into the bulk of tonight=E2=80=99s issue=E2=80=94a =
survey of seasoned Wall Street executives on the first lunatic month of <st=
rong>Trump </strong>II=E2=80=94a few observations from my trip up north. Fi=
rst, I highly recommend R=C3=A9flexion Charlevoix for anyone seeking a <em>=
seriously</em> remote respite from the daily grind. The two cabins, modern =
and simple,
are clad with mirrors and overlook the massive St. Lawrence Seaway. This pl=
ace gets snow, too=E2=80=94lots and lots of it, if that=E2=80=99s your thin=
g.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I=E2=80=99m also happy to report that it is entirely=
 possible to drive from New York through Quebec to Charlevoix and charge yo=
ur electric vehicle in a relatively efficient manner along the way, especia=
lly if you have access to Tesla superchargers, as we Rivian owners sometime=
s
do. (The trip required four 30-minute charging stops each way.) Ordinarily,=
 I=E2=80=99d recommend against driving for 10 hours, especially in an E.V. =
in the dead of winter, but our initial plans=E2=80=94flying to Montreal and=
 driving the four hours to Charlevoix=E2=80=94were lavished by treacherous =
weather, so it was drive or nothing. In any case, the trip confirmed the sc=
ale of the obstacles to broader E.V. adoption. The U.S. will need something=
 like 30 million charging ports by 2030, according to industry groups; as
of late last year, only around 200,000 public charging ports had been built=
=2E Canada, by contrast, seems to have=20=
more charging stations per capita.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">Things got a little nuttier on the drive home, alas, as we=
 ran into a serious delay at the U.S. border crossing that would probably b=
e music to Trump=E2=80=99s ears. There were 10 booths for U.S. immigration =
agents to accommodate cars with, and on Monday night=E2=80=94the end
of the long holiday weekend=E2=80=94only two were open. A changeable messag=
e sign warned, in French, of two-hour delays; it took four. We joined the q=
ueue at 6 p.m. and got through the booth at 10 p.m., having consumed the en=
tire Duke-UVA basketball game via internet radio. (Sorry, <strong>Paul Tudo=
r Jones</strong>.) I briefly entertained the thought that this was the doin=
g of border czar <strong>Tom Homan</strong>, perhaps to punish Americans fo=
r venturing into Canada. The good news was that the Tesla
supercharger in North Hudson, New York=E2=80=94250 miles from Manhattan=E2=
=80=94was fully functioning at midnight on a frigid holiday weekend. The Su=
noco station across the street, however, was shuttered and sepulchral.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;"><em>But enough about Canada. Back to matters closer to home=E2=80=A6<=
/em></p></div>
